|Career total\n! 248 !! 62 !! 6 !! 1 !! 23 !! 5 !! 11 !! 1 !! 288 !! 69\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''[[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]]:'''\n* [[List of A-League champions|A-League Championship]]: [[2007\u201308 A-League|2007\u201308]]\n\n'''[[Sydney FC]]:'''\n* [[List of A-League champions|A-League Premiership]]: [[2009\u201310 A-League|2009\u201310]]\n* [[List of A-League champions|A-League Championship]]: [[2009\u201310 A-League|2009\u201310]]\n\n'''[[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]]:'''\n* [[List of A-League champions|A-League Premiership]]: [[2012\u201313 A-League|2012\u201313]]\n* [[AFC Champions League]]: [[2014 AFC Champions League|2014]]\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]] Players Player: 2006-07\n* [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]] Player of the Year: [[2012\u201313 Western Sydney Wanderers FC season|2012\u201313]]\n* [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]]  Player of the Year: 2015-16\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerway|mark-bridge/17556}}\n* {{FIFA player|229017}}\n\n{{Western Sydney Wanderers FC Player of the Year}}\n{{Australia Squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Western Sydney Wanderers FC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridge, Mark}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australia international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australia under-20 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Olympic soccer players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Parramatta Power players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle Jets FC players]]\n[[Category:Sydney FC players]]\n[[Category:Western Sydney Wanderers FC players]]\n[[Category:Tianjin Teda F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chiangrai United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:National Soccer League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Parramatta FC players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Mounties Wanderers FC players]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:NPL\u2192National Premier Leagues", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Ping An Insurance", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Ping An Insurance\n| logo                = Ping_An_Insurance_logo.svg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| image               = Ping'an International Financial Center in June 2017 from 3rd Fuhua Rd.jpg\n| image_caption       = [[Ping An Finance Centre]], [[Futian District]], [[Shenzhen]]\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{ubl|{{SSE|601318}} (A share)|{{SEHK|2318}} (H share)}}\n| genre               = \n| foundation          = {{start date and age|1988}}\n| founder             = [[Ma&nbsp;Mingzhe]]\n| location            = \n| location_city       = [[Shenzhen]]\n| location_country    = China\n| origins             = \n| key_people          = [[Ma&nbsp;Mingzhe]]&nbsp;([[Chairman]]&nbsp;&&nbsp;[[CEO]])\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| industry            = Financial Services\n| products            = \n| services            = {{bulleted list |Life and Health Insurance |Property and Casualty |Banking |Asset Management |Fintech and Healthtech}}\n| revenue             = {{increase}} {{CNY|1.273&nbsp;trillion}}\n| revenue_year        = 2019\n| operating_income    = {{increase}} {{CNY|132.9&nbsp;billion}}\n| income_year         = 2019\n| net_income          = {{increase}} {{CNY|149.4&nbsp;billion}}\n| net_income_year     = 2019\n| assets              = {{increase}} {{CNY|8.222&nbsp;trillion}}\n| assets_year         = 2019\n| equity              = {{increase}} {{CNY|852.3&nbsp;billion}}\n| equity_year         = 2019\n| num_employees       = Approx. 190,000<ref>https://www.pgmcapital.com/why-investing-in-ping-an-insurance-group-can-be-lucrative/</ref>\n| parent              = \n| divisions           = \n| owner               = {{bulleted list |CP Group Ltd. (8.97%) |Shenzhen Investment Holdings Co., Ltd.(5.27%) }}{{ubl|(as of 31 December 2019) }}\n| rating              = \n| homepage            = [http://www.pingan.cn http://www.pingan.cn]\n| footnotes           = in a consolidated basis<ref name=Pingan2018AR>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2016/0329/LTN201603291073.pdf|title=2018 Audited Results|date=12 March 2019|access-date=9 April 2019|work=Ping An Insurance|publisher=Hong Kong Stock Exchange|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021010126/http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2016/0329/LTN201603291073.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Ping An Insurance''' known also as '''Ping An of China''' ({{zh|c=\u4e2d\u56fd\u5e73\u5b89|p=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 P\u00edng \u0100n}}), full name '''Ping An Insurance (Group) Company of China, Ltd.''' is a Chinese [[holding company|holding conglomerate]] whose subsidiaries mainly deal with [[insurance]], [[banking]], and [[financial services]]. The company was founded in 1988 and is headquartered in [[Shenzhen]]. \"Ping An\" literally means \"safe and well\".\n\nPing An ranked 7th on the Forbes Global 2000 list and 29th on the Fortune Global 500 list.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clay Chandler |title=China\u2019s Biggest Private Sector Company Is Betting Its Future on Data |url=https://fortune.com/longform/ping-an-big-data/ |website=Forbes and Fortune |access-date=2019-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920145011/https://fortune.com/longform/ping-an-big-data |archive-date=2019-09-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company is considered to be China's biggest insurer, with US$107 billion in gross premium income in 2018. Its market capitalization is at US$220 billion in July 2019, making it the world's largest insurer except for Berkshire Hathaway.<ref>{{cite web |title=Largest insurance companies worldwide as of July 2019, by market capitalization |url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/431547/leading-insurance-companies-worldwide-by-market-cap/ |website=Statista}}</ref>\n\nPing An Insurance is one of the [[SSE 50 Index|top 50 companies]] in the Shanghai Stock Exchange.<ref>{{cite web |title=Data center |url=http://data.eastmoney.com/other/index/sz50.html |website=East Money}}</ref> It is also a constituent stock of Hang Seng Index, an index of the top 50 companies in the Hong Kong Stock Exchange.<ref>{{cite web |title=HSI |url=http://www.aastocks.com/tc/stocks/market/index/hk-index-con.aspx |website=AAstocks}}</ref> Ping An Insurance was also included in the pan-China stock indices [[CSI 300 Index]], [[FTSE China A50 Index]] and [[Hang Seng China 50 Index]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pgmcapital.com/why-investing-in-ping-an-insurance-group-can-be-lucrative/|title=Why Investing in Ping An Insurance Group can be Lucrative \u2013 PGM Capital|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nPing An Insurance has been selected for the 2019 Dow Jones Sustainability Emerging Markets Index (DJSI). It was the first insurance company from mainland China to be selected on the index.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ping An ups sustainability credential with leading index inclusion |url=https://esg.theasset.com/ESG/38849/ping-an-ups-sustainability-credential-with-leading-index-inclusion |website=The Asset}}</ref> Ping An is a signatory of the United Nations-supported Principles for Responsible Investment (PRI), and was the first asset owner in mainland China to join.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ping An named to Dow Jones Sustainability Index |url=https://www.insurancebusinessmag.com/asia/news/breaking-news/ping-an-named-to-dow-jones-sustainability-index-178905.aspx |website=Insurance Business Asia |publisher=Gabriel Olano |accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nPing An Insurance consistently ranks as the world's top global insurance brand, and as of 2018, was the third most valuable global financial brand in the world.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ping An Ranks 40th in BrandZ\u2122 Global Brands; Tops Global Insurance Brand List for 4\u1d57\u02b0 Consecutive Year |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ping-an-ranks-40th-in-brandz-global-brands-tops-global-insurance-brand-list-for-4th-consecutive-year-300865599.html |website=Cision}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\n'''Ping An Insurance Group''' started off in 1988 as a property and casualty insurance company, later diversifying into life insurance, banking, asset management, brokerage services and private equity investing. But it is Ping An's embrace of technology, with an array of financial technology platforms and services for customers, that has made it a diversified financial conglomerate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ping An ups the digital stakes in China and beyond |url=https://www.euromoney.com/article/b1b3djz89qjmhr/ping-an-ups-the-digital-stakes-in-china-and-beyond |website=AsiaMoney |access-date=2019-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801055255/https://www.euromoney.com/article/b1b3djz89qjmhr/ping-an-ups-the-digital-stakes-in-china-and-beyond |archive-date=2019-08-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPing An is one of the few companies in China with licenses to offer a full suite of financial services, including insurance, banking, trusts, securities, futures and financial leasing.<ref>{{cite web |title=China's Ping An Insurance aims to join Alibaba, Tencent ranks as tech behemoth |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/China-s-Ping-An-Insurance-aims-to-join-Alibaba-Tencent-ranks-as-tech-behemoth |website=Nikkei Asian Review |access-date=2019-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104052540/https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/China-s-Ping-An-Insurance-aims-to-join-Alibaba-Tencent-ranks-as-tech-behemoth |archive-date=2019-11-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSince the mid-1990s Ping An has been diversifying into financial services from its core business of insurance and began taking investments from overseas firms. Ping An accepted investments from [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Goldman Sachs]] in 1994. In 2002 [[HSBC]] took a large equity interest in Ping An.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationalinvestment.net/internationalinvestment/news/3505920/china-8217-ping-overtakes-blackrock-hsbc-8217-biggest-shareholder|title=China\u2019s Ping An overtakes BlackRock to become HSBC\u2019s biggest shareholder|date=2018-11-07|website=www.internationalinvestment.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In early 2008, Ping An agreed to take a 50% share in Fortis Investments, a subsidiary of [[Fortis (finance)|Fortis]],<ref>[http://english.caijing.com.cn/2008-04-03/100055137.html The Ping An-Fortis Deal: Who Really Wins?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721182614/http://english.caijing.com.cn/2008-04-03/100055137.html |date=2011-07-21 }}, Caijing Magazine, 3 April 2008</ref> which had taken over ABN AMRO Asset Management as a result of the split up of [[ABN AMRO]] in late 2007, but the deal was cancelled in October 2008.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn June 2009, Ping An became a strategic investor in [[Shenzhen Development Bank]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jun2009/gb20090614_511195.htm |title=Ping An to invest in Shenzhen Development Bank - BusinessWeek |work=businessweek.com |year=2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418120537/http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jun2009/gb20090614_511195.htm |archivedate=18 April 2011 }}</ref> (now part of [[Ping An Bank]]). In 2016, Ping An invested more overseas.<ref name=\"Fortune Article in August\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 18, 2016 |title=China\u2019s Ping An Eyes an Overseas Splurge, Possibly in the UK |url=http://fortune.com/2016/08/18/china-ping-an-insurance-uk-investment/ |newspaper=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |location=I don't know |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214175713/http://fortune.com/2016/08/18/china-ping-an-insurance-uk-investment/ |archive-date=February 14, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January in 2017, Deputy Head Cai Lifeng resigned for personal reasons.<ref name=\"Reuters Brief on Deputy Head Resigning\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=January 25, 2017 |title=BRIEF-Ping An Bank's deputy head of the bank resigns |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL4N1FF3CV |newspaper=[[Reuters]] |location= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318010104/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL4N1FF3CV |archive-date=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Technology-Powered Business Transformation===\nPing An invests 1% of its revenues into R&D, which is 10% of its profit every year, on new technologies of AI, Blockchain and Cloud Computing for ten years to transform its financial services and support the building of its five ecosystems: financial services, health care, auto services, real estate services and smart city services.<ref name=\"Shu-Ching Jean Chen\">{{cite web |title=Chinese Giant Ping An Looks Beyond Insurance To A Fintech Future |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shuchingjeanchen/2018/06/06/chinese-giant-ping-an-looks-beyond-insurance-to-a-fintech-future/#32237f8748f3 |website=Forbes |publisher=Shu-Ching Jean Chen |accessdate=5 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624141044/https://www.forbes.com/sites/shuchingjeanchen/2018/06/06/chinese-giant-ping-an-looks-beyond-insurance-to-a-fintech-future/#32237f8748f3 |archive-date=24 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> More than 576 million users and 100 Chinese cities are connected to at least one of those ecosystems.<ref>{{cite web |title=China\u2019s Insurance Giant Is Morphing Into a Tech Company |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-02/ping-an-co-ceos-talk-about-the-chinese-insurer-s-move-into-tech?from=groupmessage&isappinstalled=0 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref> Over the years, Ping An has successfully launched fintech and healthtech businesses such as Lufax Holding, OneConnect, Ping An Good Doctor (1833.HK), and Ping An HealthKonnect.<ref name=\"Pingan2018AR\" />\n\nSupporting Business Development with Three Core Technologies \n*AI: With the philosophy of \u201cchange people\u2019s lives for the better in ways and forms\u201d, Ping An is applying its AI technologies in financial, healthcare and smart city services.<ref>{{cite web |title=AI as a Force for Good |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/611551/ai-as-a-force-for-good/ |website=MIT Technology Review |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> Ping An has world-leading facial, voiceprint and medical image recognition technologies. It is number one in AI medical imaging, for instance, with more than 95% accuracy in the authoritative LUNA rankings for imaging in two categories for lung diseases.<ref name=\"Shu-Ching Jean Chen\"/>\n*Blockchain: Ping An's OneConnect platform is one of the largest commercial blockchain platform in the world with over 44,000 blockchain nodes providing services to over 3,000 financial institutions. Through its self-developed FiMAX proprietary blockchain technology, its zero-knowledge proof algorithm and low latency design is able to reach 50,000 transactions per second.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chinese Giant Ping An Claims to Have Over 44,000 Nodes on Its Commercial Blockchain Platform |url=https://news.8btc.com/chinese-giant-ping-an-claims-to-have-over-44000-nodes-on-its-commercial-blockchain-platform |website=8BTC |publisher=Lylian Teng |accessdate=5 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705085252/https://news.8btc.com/chinese-giant-ping-an-claims-to-have-over-44000-nodes-on-its-commercial-blockchain-platform |archive-date=5 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Cloud Computing: Ping An Cloud offers efficient and secure services for industries in finance, health care, auto, real estate and smart city. In 2018, Ping An Cloud successfully became GitHub's first managed serviced provider (MSP) in Greater China.<ref name=\"Pingan2018AR\" /> GitHub will provide GitHub Enterprise products and services to China enterprises through Ping An Cloud.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ping An Announces Full Upgrading of Ping An Cloud; Now Offers Services to External Customers & Sets Up Strategic Partnership with GitHub |url=https://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2018/10/140240-ping-an-announces-full-upgrading-of-ping-an-cloud-now-offers-services-to-external-customers-sets-up-strategic-partnership-with-github/ |website=Crowdfund Insider |publisher=Samantha Hurst |accessdate=5 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705085251/https://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2018/10/140240-ping-an-announces-full-upgrading-of-ping-an-cloud-now-offers-services-to-external-customers-sets-up-strategic-partnership-with-github/ |archive-date=5 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Ownership==\nPing An is completely a publicly listed company.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chinese Giant Ping An Looks Beyond Insurance To A Fintech Future |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shuchingjeanchen/2018/06/06/chinese-giant-ping-an-looks-beyond-insurance-to-a-fintech-future/#24aea27d48f3 |website=Forbes |publisher=Shu-Ching Jean Chen}}</ref> It is China's first joint-stock insurance company. Beginning in the 1990s, Ping An took advantage of widening reforms to become the first Chinese financial institution in which foreign firms could own equity: Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were early backers. The company eventually went public in 2004, listing in Hong Kong and subsequently also listed in Shanghai in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=China\u2019s Biggest Private Sector Company Is Betting Its Future on Data |url=https://fortune.com/longform/ping-an-big-data/ |website=Forbes |publisher=Clay Chandler}}</ref>\n\nThere is no controlling shareholder, nor de facto controller. As at 31 December 2018, CP Group is the biggest investor in Ping An, holding 9.19% stake. Shenzhen Government via Shenzhen Investment Holdings (Chinese: \u6df1\u5733\u5e02\u6295\u8cc7\u63a7\u80a1) and Shum Yip Group (Chinese: \u6df1\u4e1a\u96c6\u56e2), still owned a combined 6.68% stake (5.27% + 1.41%) as the second largest shareholder.<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Annual report |url=https://www1.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/sehk/2019/0328/ltn20190328613.pdf |website=HKEX news |publisher=Pingan}}</ref>\n\nPing An has the classification as being a [[civilian-run enterprise]]. [[Richard McGregor]], author of ''[[The Party: The Secret World of China's Communist Rulers]]'',<ref>{{cite book |last1=McGregor |first1=Richard |title=The Party: The Secret World of China's Communist Rulers |date=2010 |publisher=Allen Lane |location=New York, 2012}}</ref> said that \"the true ownership of large chunks of its shares remains unclear\" and that the ownership of Ping An is a \"murky structure\".<ref name=McGregor204205>[[Richard McGregor|McGregor]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=TxchbfKHfhsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Party&source=bl&ots=9OnO-rN4ax&sig=1G4BwYchwkh6g-H7BEKWwUtusnA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GzVqUJmjJcXL0AHCj4HQDA&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Huawei&f=false p. 204] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220055739/https://books.google.com/books?id=TxchbfKHfhsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Party&source=bl&ots=9OnO-rN4ax&sig=1G4BwYchwkh6g-H7BEKWwUtusnA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GzVqUJmjJcXL0AHCj4HQDA&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Huawei&f=false |date=2017-02-20 }}-205.</ref> In October 2012, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that relatives and associates of Chinese [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] [[Wen Jiabao]] controlled stakes in Ping An worth at least US$2.2 billion in 2007.<ref>David Barboza, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/26/business/global/family-of-wen-jiabao-holds-a-hidden-fortune-in-china.html?_r=1& \"Billions in Hidden Riches for Family of Chinese Leader\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519051035/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/26/business/global/family-of-wen-jiabao-holds-a-hidden-fortune-in-china.html?_r=1& |date=2017-05-19 }}, ''The New York Times'', 25 October 2012. Retrieved 27 October 2012.</ref> They paid the equivalent of 40 cents a share, others buying at the same time paid as much as $1.20. Thanks to favourable regulatory treatment and licensing, the firm was able to build a diversified financial firm with interests in insurance, brokerage, and banking.<ref name=NYT112412>{{cite news|title=Lobbying, a Windfall and a Leader\u2019s Family|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/25/business/chinese-insurers-regulatory-win-benefits-a-leaders-family.html|accessdate=November 26, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 24, 2012|author=David Barboza|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121125161910/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/25/business/chinese-insurers-regulatory-win-benefits-a-leaders-family.html|archive-date=November 25, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Premier Wen Jiabao's family responded back to The New York Time's report, claiming its  statement about their family's wealth is \"untrue\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1071466/wen-jiabaos-family-says-claims-hidden-fortune-are-lies|title=Wen Jiabao's family says claims of hidden fortune are 'lies|last1=Chan|first1=Minnie|date=|website=SCMP|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927043052/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1071466/wen-jiabaos-family-says-claims-hidden-fortune-are-lies|archive-date=2019-09-27|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> Two lawyers later released a statement on behalf of Wen's family denying the other claims made, and asserting that the premier's 90-year-old mother has never held a US$120 million of Ping An Insurance's investment, as the paper had reported.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wen family hits back at 'lies' on hidden fortune |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1071504/wen-family-hits-back-lies-hidden-fortune |website=SCMP |publisher=Minnie Chan, Teddy Ng |access-date=2019-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927051521/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1071504/wen-family-hits-back-lies-hidden-fortune |archive-date=2019-09-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[HSBC]] acquired 48.22% of H shares by means of different HSBC subsidiaries<ref name=Pingan2009AR>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2010/0427/LTN201004271085.pdf|title=2009 Annual Report|date=27 April 2010|access-date=20 October 2016|work=Ping An Insurance|publisher=archive of Hong Kong Stock Exchange|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021010233/http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2010/0427/LTN201004271085.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ([[H share]] accounted for 34.83% of the share capital as at 31 December 2009,<ref name=Pingan2009AR/> which was later increased to 41.88% in 2015 <ref name=Pingan2015AR>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2016/0329/LTN201603291073.pdf|title=2015 Annual Report|date=29 March 2016|access-date=20 October 2016|work=Ping An Insurance|publisher=Hong Kong Stock Exchange|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021010126/http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2016/0329/LTN201603291073.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>). HSBC hold 16.80% of total shares of Ping An, making itself to be the biggest shareholder at 31 December 2009.<ref name=Pingan2009AR/>\n\nOn 5 December 2012, HSBC announced to sell their entire 15.57% stake for [[Hong Kong dollar|HK$]]72.736&nbsp;[[1,000,000,000|billion]] (approx. US$9.385&nbsp;billion; HK$59.00 per share) to Thailand conglomerate [[Charoen Pokphand]]. The deal would split into two phases, which the latter was subjected to the clearance from [[China Insurance Regulatory Commission]], which would paid in cash and a loan from China Development Bank to Charoen Pokphand.<ref name=HSBC>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsbc.com/news-and-insight/media-resources/media-releases/2012/hsbc-to-sell-its-entire-shareholding-in-ping-an-insurance|title=HSBC to sell its entire shareholding in Ping An Insurance|date=5 February 2012|access-date=20 October 2016|publisher=HSBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021004349/http://www.hsbc.com/news-and-insight/media-resources/media-releases/2012/hsbc-to-sell-its-entire-shareholding-in-ping-an-insurance|archive-date=21 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2013 Charoen Pokphand got the clearance.{{failed verification|date=October 2016}}<ref name=ref2013020407>{{Cite news\n    | title = Thai tycoons go for it in multi-billion deals\n    | publisher = Investvine.com\n    | date = 2013-02-04\n    | url = http://investvine.com/thai-tycoons-go-for-it/\n    | accessdate = 2013-03-17\n    | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130212084623/http://investvine.com/thai-tycoons-go-for-it/\n    | archive-date = 2013-02-12\n    | url-status = live\n    }}</ref> On 10 May in spite of a lack of loan from the state-owned China Development Bank to Charoen Pokphand,<ref name=\"MW\">{{cite web | url=http://www.morningwhistle.com/html/2013/FinanceMarkets_0108/216505.html | title=China Development Bank stops loan to Charoen Pokphand to buy Ping An | publisher=Morning Whistle | date=January 8, 2013 | accessdate=2013-05-10 | author=Chen Xiaoyi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117112419/http://www.morningwhistle.com/html/2013/FinanceMarkets_0108/216505.html | archive-date=January 17, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite web | url=http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1146336/still-too-much-murkiness-around-details-ping-deal | title=Still too much murkiness around the details of the Ping An deal | publisher=South China Morning Post | date=9 February 2013 | accessdate=2013-05-10 | author=Yam, Shirley | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219005433/http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1146336/still-too-much-murkiness-around-details-ping-deal | archive-date=19 February 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> the deal was completed.<ref name=\"SCMP\"/><ref name=\"Bloomberg HK\">{{cite web | url=http://www.scmp.com/business/banking-finance/article/1097953/ping-rises-hsbc-stake-sale-charoen-pokphand | title=Ping An rises on HSBC stake sale to Charoen Pokphand | publisher=Bloomberg Hong Kong | date=5 December 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-10 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202012300/http://www.scmp.com/business/banking-finance/article/1097953/ping-rises-hsbc-stake-sale-charoen-pokphand | archive-date=2 February 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> According to HSBC, the transaction would increase Tier 1 [[Capital ratio]] of the bank for 0.5%, as well as a post-tax gain of US$2.6&nbsp;billion.<ref name=HSBC/> HSBC had an above average forecasted CET1 ratio of 8.5% in [[2011 European Union bank stress test]] under the adverse scenario,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stress-test.eba.europa.eu/documents/10180/15935/Summary+of+CT1+ratios+under+the+adverse+scenario.pdf/986761b3-0a69-40fc-a92d-a651fe074505|title=Results of the 2011 EU-wide Stress Test under the adverse scenario|date=18 July 2011|access-date=20 October 2016|publisher=European Banking Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021004254/http://stress-test.eba.europa.eu/documents/10180/15935/Summary+of+CT1+ratios+under+the+adverse+scenario.pdf/986761b3-0a69-40fc-a92d-a651fe074505|archive-date=21 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> nevertheless HSBC chose to strengthen its capital by selling Ping An. The actual ratio at 31 December 2012 was 12.3%, increased 2.2% year-to-yearly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsbc.com/~/media/hsbc-com/investorrelationsassets/annual-results/pdfs/hsbc2012ara0.pdf|title=2012 Annual Report and Accounts|date=4 March 2013|access-date=20 October 2016|publisher=HSBC Holdings|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140207134643/http://www.hsbc.com/~/media/HSBC-com/InvestorRelationsAssets/annual-results/pdfs/hsbc2012ara0.pdf|archive-date=7 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Markets ==\nSince 24 June 2004 Ping An has been listed on the [[Hong Kong Stock Exchange]]. {{Sehk|02318}}\nNow,{{when|date=October 2016}} it has a listing on stock exchange in Shanghai, {{SSE|601318}}.\n\nPing An was chosen as an index stock of the [[Hang Seng China Enterprises Index]] (HSCEI),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pingan.com/about/en/news_70112.jsp|title=Ping An Insurance Becomes Constituent Stock of Hang Seng Index|date=11 May 2007|publisher=Ping An Insurance|access-date=15 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207005153/https://www.pingan.com/about/en/news_70112.jsp|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> replacing [[Anhui Expressway]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nThe Hang Seng Index Services Company announced on 11 May 2007 that Ping An would join as [[Hang Seng Index|Hang Seng Index Constituent Stock]] ([[Blue chip (stock market)|Blue Chip]] Stock) effective on 4 June 2007.\n\n== Operations ==\nPing An has operations across all of the People's Republic of China, and in Hong Kong and Macau through Ping An Insurance Overseas. Lufax, OneConnect and Ping An Good Doctor have now expanded overseas. OneConnect is in 10 countries outside of China, serving about 27 top institutional financials.<ref>{{cite web |title=CNBC Transcript: Jessica Tan, Co-CEO, Ping An Group |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/20/cnbc-transcript-jessica-tan-co-ceo-ping-an-group.html |website=CNBC}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n[https://apnews.com/PR%20Newswire/52ff7bee2d4ed3e0379bd4927afce052 \u201cPing An Donates \u00a31.1m of COVID-19 Medical Supplies to United Kingdom\u201d], <ref>Associated Press</ref>, 3 April, 2020.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.pingan.com.cn Company web site 1] {{in lang|zh}}\n* [http://www.pinganfinancecenter.com New building under construction, ready in 2016]\n* [http://www.pa18.com/pa18Web/framework/aboutus_en.jsp?content=http://www.pa18.com/pa18Docc/docc/aboutus/english/index.htm Company web site 2]\n* [http://www.bobsguide.com/guide/news/2010/Mar/15/Ping_An_Asset_Management_goes_live_with_HiPortfolio%C2%AE.html News website about Ping An systems upgrade]\n\n{{SSE 50 companies}}\n{{Hang Seng}}\n{{Navboxes\n